{{Infobox person | name= Chris Meek | image =Chris Meek.jpg | birth_date= {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1970|9|30}} | birth_place= [[Elmira, New York]], U.S. | party= [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] | residence= [[Stamford, Connecticut]], U.S. | alma_mater= [[Syracuse University]] and [[Pace University]] | profession= [[Philanthropist]] and Financial Services Executive | religion= [[Presbyterian]] | website = [http://www.soldiersocks.com/ SoldierSocks.com] }}
'''Christopher Douglas Meek''' (born September 30, 1970) is a [[philanthropist]] and American businessman. Meek is a Financial Services Executive and is the founder and Chairman of [[START Now!]]<ref>[http://www.startnowct.org START Now!]</ref> and [[Soldiersocks]]. He is a member of the Board of Directors of Career Resources<ref>http://www.careerresources.org</ref> (Bridgeport, Connecticut) and the World Affairs Forum.<ref>http://www.worldaffairsforum.org/about_us.htm#BOARD%20OF%20DIRECTORS</ref> Meek is the past Chairman of the Board of Directors of the [http://www.yerwoodcenter.com/ Yerwood Center] ([[Stamford, Connecticut]]). He also served as Vice Chairman of the Board of Directors at St Luke's LifeWorks<ref>http://www.stlukeslifeworks.org</ref> and is the past Chairman of the Development Committee as well as the Life Long Learning Committee there. Meek is also currently serving as the Chairman on Stamford's Urban Redevelopment Commission <ref>http://www.cityofstamford.org/content/25/50/2234/default.aspx.</ref> Chris Meek, father of four, lives in Stamford.
==Early life== Meek was born in 1970 in [[Elmira, New York]] to Douglas and Camille Meek. After his parents divorced in 1972 and after a brief time in Florida, Meek and his mother moved back to Elmira, NY and lived with his grandparents, George and Marion Giroux, until 1981.
==Education== Meek attended and graduated from [[Elmira Free Academy]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2012}} In 1992, Meek graduated from [[Syracuse University]] with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in Economics and Political Science from the [[Maxwell School]] of Citizenship and Public Affairs (Syracuse University)<ref>http://www.maxwell.syr.edu Maxwell School of Syracuse University.</ref> A member of [[Delta Tau Delta]] Fraternity, Meek earned a degree in [[Finance|Financial Management]] at [[Pace University]] (New York, New York) and later graduated with a MBA in 1999.{{Citation needed|date=March 2012}} While attending Syracuse University, he interned for U.S. Senator [[Al D'Amato]] from 1990-1992 in his Syracuse Regional Office.{{Citation needed|date=March 2012}} This internship led to Senator D’Amato asking Meek to take a senior role in his Central New York Re-Election campaign committee during the 1992 Senatorial Race against New York State Attorney General [[Robert Abrams]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2012}}
==Career== After graduating from [[Syracuse University]] in 1992,<ref>http://sumagazine.syr.edu/2009fall-winter/alumnijournal</ref> Meek worked for [[Metropolitan Life Insurance Company]] in Syracuse, New York from 1992–93 and then for [[Dean Witter Reynolds]] from 1993-95. In October 1995, Meek moved from Syracuse to New York City and began working for [[Hull Trading Company]], a [[Chicago]]-based options market-making firm.{{Citation needed|date=March 2012}} In July 1999, Hull was acquired by [[Goldman Sachs]] and Company. Meek ran the firms’ floor-based trading operations from 1999-2002.{{Citation needed|date=March 2012}} Since then, Meek has served as a Financial Services Executive in [[New York City]].{{where?|date=March 2012}}
==Community activism== In April 2009, Meek held his first in a series of loan modification events at the Yerwood Center in Stamford.<ref>http://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/banksandfinance/5174186/US-clutches-at-straws-of-recovery.html "US clutches at straws of recovery"</ref> The event consisted of five banks and several agencies offering foreclosure assistance. The program enabled 36 families to modify their mortgage, avoid going into foreclosure and losing their homes.<ref name=autogenerated1>[http://www.stamfordadvocate.com/default/article/Together-we-can-accomplish-anything-1005879.php "Together we can accomplish anything"]</ref> Meek created the not-for-profit [[START Now!]] in May 2009.<ref>http://www.stamfordadvocate.com/news/article/Goldman-Sachs-exec-brings-foreclosure-counseling-1253022.php "Goldman Sachs' exec brings foreclosure counseling show to Bridgeport"</ref>
In July 2009, Meek received a request asking for help in obtaining hygienic items for our American soldiers fighting in [[Afghanistan]]. This led him to create the not-for-profit [[Soldier socks]].<ref>http://www.connecticutplus.com/cplus/information/news/Local_2/Stamford-resident-launches-non-profit-organization-to-aide-troops-serving-abroad63176317.shtml</ref><ref>http://www.stamfordplus.com/stm/information/nws1/publish/News_1/Fedele-to-help-local-group-pack-items-for-troops6816.shtml</ref>
==Politics== On August 24, 2010, Meek was sworn in to a 3-year term by Stamford Mayor [[Michael Pavia]] as [[Commissioner]] on the City's Urban Redevelopment Committee (URC) and was elected Chairman of the Commission on December 13, 2012.<ref>http://www.cityofstamford.org/content/25/50/2234/4368/4384/default.aspx.</ref> In October 2011, Chris was awarded the 2011 March of Dimes Franklin Delano Roosevelt Outstanding Corporate Citizen Award.<ref>http://www.marchofdimes.com/connecticut/1498_27480.asp</ref>
On October 17, 2011 Meek announced his candidacy to represent [[Connecticut's 4th congressional district]].<ref>http://www.newstimes.com/news/article/Activist-starts-4th-District-campaign-2275088.php</ref> Meek had previously been mentioned<ref>[http://www.rollcall.com/issues/56_49/-200722-1.html ''Roll Call'' reference to Chris Meek]</ref> as a potential candidate for the United States Senate in 2012. ''Connecticut Magazine'''s inaugural <ref>http://www.connecticutmag.com/Connecticut-Magazine/March-2011/40-Under-40/index.php?cparticle=8&siarticle=7</ref> "40 under 40" honoring the state's next generation of leaders named Meek as one of the forty new young leaders who are "full of energy, ideas and the determination to steer an unswerving course into the future".
